Initiatives aim
to raise minority
retention rates

By Jack Finn
Asst. News Editor

Minority recruitment and retention is the focal
point of several initiatives at Pitt this summer.

“Minorities are historically disadvantaged groups
such as African—Americans, Hispanics and Native
Americans,” senate student affairs committee Chair
Jonathan Schooler said.

The student affairs committee sponsored a resolu-
tion addressing minority retention that was
approved by the Faculty Assembly and the Senate
Council and forwarded to Pitt Chancellor J. Dennis
O’Connor, according to Schooler.

The Minority Retention Resolution contains four
elements:

-The Office of Enrollment Management is to
develop a coordinated system to manage minority
retention. Current evaluation, program recommen-
dations, program development, liaison and formal
reporting would all be functions of the management
program.

-The Mentor Challenge Scholarship Program
would select upperclass and graduate students who
would perform as mentors for incoming first—year
minority students.

Scholarship awards and Honors Convocation
recognition would be partqof the program.

°The introduction of cultural—diversity issues into
the curriculum, promoting minority research and
expansion of university workshops that concentrate
on diversity. Familiarizing people with alternative
perspectives and ways- in which unintended offenses
may occur is a goal. _ ‘

°Contributions to address target funding for
minority retention and recmitment. Additional schol-
arships and minority programs would be fund uses.

“The attrition rate for minority students is 51.1 per-
cent as compared to 55.6 percent for white stu-
dents,” Schooler said.

These figures were for 1985 through 1990. If a stu-
dent was enrolled in 1985 but was no longer
enrolled‘ or had not graduated by 1990, they were
considered to be part of the attrition rate, according
to Schooler.

“This represents a substantial difference and is the
cause for our concern,” Schooler said.

Vice Provost Jack Daniel has recently implement-
ed a three-level program aimed at minority reten~
tion.

“Chancellor O’Connor has approved five graduate
fellows in honor of K. Leroy Irvis, five undergradu~
ate scholarships in honor of Helen Faison, and six

post-doctoral awards for research, all targeted for,

minorities,” Daniel said.

The three levels of scholarship awards are intend-
ed to enhance the opportunities for minorities at
Pitt, according to Daniel.

