Harassment policy needs revised

From July 1, 1992 until June 50, 1993, Pitt’s Office of
Affirmative Action dealt with 17 cases of alleged sexual
harassment.

Although the number may seem low, assistant director
of affirmative action Elaine Frampton said she believes
otherwise.“It’s much more prevalent than statistics or data
reflect,” Frampton said. .

Pitt’s definition of sexual harassment involves unwel-
come sexual advances, requests or comments in three
cases: 1. When submission to remarks affects academic or
employment success. 2. When submission or rejection
affects an academic or employment decision. 3. When the
conduct affects performance or creates a hostile or offen-
sive environment.

Although Pitt’s policy is to prohibit sexual harassment,
the university community needs to be aware of the defini-
tion as well as their policy. The fact that a policy exists is
not enough. 1

Although we commend the staff of the Office of
Affirmative Action for sponsoring workshops and educa-
tional seminars for faculty and staff, more students need
to be educated and made aware of where to turn if they
are the victim of harassment.

As well as making students aware, changes in the policy
are needed. The procedure suggests that the first step to
be taken when there is a complaint of sexual harassment
is an informal resolution, which recommends that “the
complainant take individual action to resolve the problem
through written or verbal action.” This can be done alone
or with an Affirmative Action staff member serving as
mediator. The policy also states that, “every effort should
be made to resolve a problem informally.”

Frampton said that many students are afraid to report
their cases because of a fear that their grades will be low-
ered. Yet with this informal policy, Pitt would encourage
a student to personally confront a professor whose
actions are offensive.

If the informal complaint is insufficient, there is also a
Formal Complaint Resolution in which a written com-
plaint is filed with the university and involves an investi-
gation. The policy states that, “while every effort will be
made to protect the privacy rights of all parties, confiden-
tiality cannot be guaranteed.”

In both informal and formal cases the victim is unable to
remain anonymous. Such a policy discourages anyone
from filing a complaint who is afraid of the repercussions
— which only propagates the cycle of sexual harassment.
In this case of suspected sexual harassment, the offended
individual, with a member of Affirmative Action present,
could discuss the situation with the accused. Under Pitt’s
policy, if the complaint is valid the offender could simply
apologize and promise to never do it again. There would
be no punishment and no incentive to refrain from the
behaviors with other individuals.

Pitt’s sexual harassment policy needs to be more sympa-
thetic to the victims and more discouraging to those who
harass.

    
  
 
 
      
   
 
     

   
 

