Louis Mayer used to rent famous
paintings from an -art museum and
have them rotated on a regular dis-
play in his home.

Needless to say art and film have
had a conspicuous relationship in
this country. i

Shakespeare on film could be
the best example of this.
Unfortunately, Kenneth Branagh’s
Much Ado About Nothing does lit-
tle to challenge the tradition of
Shakespeare on film or the Warner
Brothers’ condescending legacy.

The fact that what Shakespeare
wrote was intended for theatres ——
its episodic narrative and scene-
based nature —— is in contrast to
film’s ability to produce seamless
narratives through location shoot-
ing, editing, voice—over, etc.
Though Shakespeare has spawned
a million spinoffs (Rosencrantz
and G-ila’enstern Are Dead is a
recent example), his plays’ appear-
ance on film is highlighted solely
by the substitution of natural loca-
tions for painted sets and little
else.

Such is the case with Much Ado.
The play Branagh calls
Shakespeare’s “most accessible”
gets a pretty standard treatment
with a few technical show-off

