Cousy, Guy Rodgers, Oscar
Robertson, Nate Archibald and
Magic Johnson as the five
greatest point guards he has
seen. “Anfernee is that type of
player  the kid has a gift.”

The gift was obvious not
only to Memphis State fans
who watched him grow up in
the local spotlight, but also to
those who watched helplessly
as Hardaway dazzled stadium
crowds with his skills.

As a Collegian, Hardaway
was the only player in the
country to register in the top
five of his conference — the
Great Midwest —— in five differ-
ent categories: points,
rebounds, assists, steals and
blocks. He led the Tigers in
points, rebounds and assists,
and two consecutive appear-

ances in the NCAAS, including
a run to the Elite Eight in his
sophomore season.

Statistically there is no argu-
ment about his greatness. But
to see him 1111'] the game is to
watch poetry on the basketball
court.

His lightning-quick precision
passes, which often stunned
lesser teammates who had trou-
ble handling the feeds, cut
through defenses like mercuric
darts in a jungle full of gangly
arms and legs.

To say that Hardaway is an
exceptional shooter is to make
a slight understatement. Also,
his first step to the hole is
sneaky-quick. Once he has a
couple of inches, he is al1—but-
impossible to stop.

The much-anticipated
Hardaway/O’Nea1 duo will

See Brame, page 9

Brame

 NEWS:wédﬁ¢’sday,*JaIy*7;‘1993“"‘ "  I‘  ‘ P‘ I I ‘ *

