prove to be an extremely
daunting combination — one
that will lead them to the
Eastern Conference Finals with-
in three years. Penny will find
the holes that come with Shaq’s
immediate size and strength,
but the most lethal hook—ups
will come when the defense
breaks down to double-team
either of them. If the defense
collapses on Hardaway, know
that the open player is going to
find the ball in his hands. If
Shaq is double—teamed,
Hardaway will find himself
with room to shoot or create.

An incredibly agile point
guard by trade, Hardaway can
comfortably slide down to
shooting guard, where -he can
shoot from the perimeter  or
penetrate  or create.

Hardaway can also play small
forward. Dennis Scott currently
occupies that station for
Orlando, but his large salary
and penchant for being injury-
prone make him a more obvi-
ous candidate for relocation ——
a must in Magic land -— than
point guard Scott Skiles or
power forward Brian Williams.

No matter the lineup,
Hardaway is guaranteed to step
in and excite from Day One.
His priorities, slightly eschewecl
from fellow money-hungry
draftees are simple. “I’m not
going to let anything stand in
my way of playing for
Orlando,”‘Hardaway said. “I

 

want to be a veteran when the
season starts.”

The world that now stands at
his fingertips was once highly
in doubt.

Hardaway missed virtually all
of his senior year at Memphis’
Treadwell High School due to
academic difficulties, and was
forced to sit out his freshmen
year at Memphis State, a victim
of Proposition 48. Then, after
conquering the scholastic
obstacles that kept him from
competing, a stray bullet nearly
ended his promising career.

During his first year of col-
lege, while visiting his cousin
and University of Tennessee
guard LaMarcus Golden’s inner-
city home, Hardaway was
struck in the foot by a bullet
fired several hundred feet from
him. While no permanent dam-
age was done, it forced him to
miss valuable practice time.

Instead of deterring the
young Hardaway from achiev-

ing, all of these incidents just
lend to the legend that has
grown from his days in junior
high school. A role model for
local kids during his two-year

‘stint as a Tiger, Hardaway

made the Dean’s List in sec-
ondary education —- after once

barely scraping by to make it

into college.

Hardaway currently partici-
pates in an anti-drug campaign
that features his likeness dis-
played prominently throughout
Memphis on billboards.
Accompanying his name and
picture are three words“ that
signify whatthe young athlete
has always exemplified -—- even
through times that would have
made lesser talents pack it up
and leave.

The three words read simply,
“Keep the Dream” —- some-
thing Penny knows much
about.

